---
import Layout from '@/layouts/Layout.astro';
import Navigation from '@/components/Navigation.astro';
import Footer from '@/components/Footer.astro';
import { Home, AlertTriangle, Shield } from 'lucide-astro';
---

<Layout title="Foundation Design Complete Guide | OBC 9.15 Requirements">
  <Navigation />
  
  <main>
    <!-- Hero Section -->
    <section class="bg-gray-100 pt-24 pb-12">
      <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
        <div class="max-w-4xl">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-2 text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">
            <a href="/" class="hover:text-red-600">Home</a>
            <span>/</span>
            <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-red-600">Blog</a>
            <span>/</span>
            <span>Foundation Design</span>
          </div>
          <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">
            Complete Foundation Design Guide: Soil, Structure & Code Requirements
          </h1>
          <p class="text-xl text-gray-600">
            Master OBC Part 9.15 requirements for footings and foundations in residential construction
          </p>
          <div class="flex items-center gap-4 mt-4 text-sm text-gray-500">
            <span>Published: January 2024</span>
            <span>•</span>
            <span>22 min read</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Main Content -->
    <article class="py-12">
      <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
          <!-- Introduction -->
          <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none mb-12">
            <p class="text-xl text-gray-700 mb-8">
              Foundation failure is catastrophic. There's no partial failure, no warning signs - when a foundation 
              goes, everything above comes with it. After 39 years of building foundations in Toronto's challenging 
              soils, we've learned that success starts with understanding soil bearing capacity, structural loads, 
              and the critical interplay between water, frost, and earth pressure. Here's your comprehensive guide 
              to OBC Part 9.15 requirements for residential footings and foundations.
            </p>

            <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-6 mb-8 border-2 border-blue-400">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3 flex items-center gap-2">
                <Home class="w-5 h-5 text-blue-600" />
                OBC Part 9.15 Application
              </h3>
              <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3">
                Section 9.15 applies to foundations that meet ALL these conditions:
              </p>
              <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                <li>• Soil bearing capacity: minimum 75 kPa (1,500 psf)</li>
                <li>• Building type: light-frame or flat ICF construction</li>
                <li>• Maximum 2 storeys with 3m floor-to-floor height</li>
                <li>• Earth pressure: equivalent to 480 kg/m³ fluid density</li>
                <li>• Well-drained conditions (no hydrostatic pressure)</li>
              </ul>
              <p class="text-gray-700 mt-3">
                <strong>Beyond these limits:</strong> Part 4 engineering required
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Soil Bearing Capacity -->
          <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">
              Critical Soil Bearing Requirements
            </h2>
            
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-8 border-2 border-gray-300">
              <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Soil Types and Bearing Capacity</h3>
              
              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg overflow-hidden border border-gray-200 mb-6">
                <table class="w-full">
                  <thead class="bg-gray-100">
                    <tr>
                      <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900">Soil Type</th>
                      <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900">Bearing Capacity</th>
                      <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900">Footing Adjustment</th>
                      <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900">Design Method</th>
                    </tr>
                  </thead>
                  <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-200">
                    <tr>
                      <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Stable soil/rock</td>
                      <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">≥75 kPa</td>
                      <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Use Table 9.15.3.4</td>
                      <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Part 9</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Loose sand/gravel</td>
                      <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">50 kPa</td>
                      <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">50% larger footings</td>
                      <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Section 9.4 or Part 4</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Soft clay</td>
                      <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">40 kPa</td>
                      <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">2× larger footings</td>
                      <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Section 9.4 or Part 4</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Fill/organic</td>
                      <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Variable</td>
                      <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Engineering required</td>
                      <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Part 4 only</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Permafrost</td>
                      <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Special</td>
                      <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Special design</td>
                      <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Part 4 only</td>
                    </tr>
                  </tbody>
                </table>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-yellow-50 rounded-lg p-4 border border-yellow-400">
                <p class="text-gray-700">
                  <strong>Toronto Clay Reality:</strong> Much of Toronto sits on Leda clay with bearing capacity 
                  of 40-60 kPa. This means many sites require either larger footings or engineered design. 
                  Always get a geotechnical report - the $2,500 investment prevents $50,000+ failures.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Structural Loads -->
          <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">
              <Shield class="inline w-6 h-6 text-red-600 mr-2" />
              Understanding Foundation Loads
            </h2>
            
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-8 border-2 border-gray-300">
              <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Forces Acting on Foundations</h3>
              
              <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
                <div>
                  <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Vertical Loads:</h4>
                  <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                    <li>• Dead load (structure weight)</li>
                    <li>• Live load (occupants/contents)</li>
                    <li>• Snow load (roof)</li>
                    <li>• Foundation self-weight</li>
                    <li>• Transfer from superstructure</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Lateral Forces:</h4>
                  <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                    <li>• Earth pressure (480 kg/m³)</li>
                    <li>• Hydrostatic pressure if present</li>
                    <li>• Wind loads transferred</li>
                    <li>• Earthquake loads</li>
                    <li>• Frost action/adfreezing</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6 mt-6">
                <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Earth Pressure Calculation:</h4>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-2">
                  OBC assumes earth pressure equivalent to fluid with 480 kg/m³ density:
                </p>
                <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                  <li>• At 1m depth: 4.7 kPa</li>
                  <li>• At 2m depth: 9.4 kPa</li>
                  <li>• At 2.4m depth: 11.3 kPa</li>
                  <li>• Compare to water: 9.8 kPa/m</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mt-3">
                  <strong>Critical:</strong> This assumes well-drained conditions. With hydrostatic pressure, 
                  forces double and Part 4 design is required.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Foundation Types -->
          <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Foundation Types Covered by Part 9</h2>
            
            <div class="space-y-6">
              <!-- Concrete Foundations -->
              <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">1. Concrete Foundations (9.15.2.1)</h3>
                <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
                  <div>
                    <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Requirements:</h4>
                    <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                      <li>• Comply with Section 9.3.1</li>
                      <li>• Minimum 15 MPa strength</li>
                      <li>• 25 MPa for garage/exterior</li>
                      <li>• Protection during curing</li>
                      <li>• Forms remain until set</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                  <div>
                    <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Critical Details:</h4>
                    <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                      <li>• Keep moist after form removal</li>
                      <li>• No freezing during cure</li>
                      <li>• Protect from rain</li>
                      <li>• Air entrainment for exterior</li>
                      <li>• Proper consolidation</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <!-- Unit Masonry -->
              <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">2. Unit Masonry Construction (9.15.2.2)</h3>
                <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
                  <div>
                    <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Block Requirements:</h4>
                    <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                      <li>• 15 MPa compressive strength</li>
                      <li>• Over net cross-section</li>
                      <li>• Type S or N mortar</li>
                      <li>• Cores vertical</li>
                      <li>• Grouted if reinforced</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                  <div>
                    <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Installation:</h4>
                    <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                      <li>• Full mortar coverage</li>
                      <li>• No freezing 24 hours</li>
                      <li>• Reinforcement centered</li>
                      <li>• Grout consolidation</li>
                      <li>• Proper curing conditions</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <!-- Pier Foundations -->
              <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">3. Pier-Type Foundations (9.15.2.3)</h3>
                <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
                  <div>
                    <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Limitations:</h4>
                    <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                      <li>• One-storey buildings only</li>
                      <li>• 3.5m maximum spacing</li>
                      <li>• Height ≤ 3× base width</li>
                      <li>• 150-250mm circular typical</li>
                      <li>• 190-290mm block piers</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                  <div>
                    <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Frost Protection:</h4>
                    <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                      <li>• Below frost line</li>
                      <li>• Anchored to footing</li>
                      <li>• Granular backfill</li>
                      <li>• Slip plane if needed</li>
                      <li>• Reinforced for tension</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <!-- Wood Frame -->
              <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">4. Wood-Frame Foundations (9.15.2.4)</h3>
                <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
                  <div>
                    <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Requirements:</h4>
                    <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                      <li>• Comply with CSA S406</li>
                      <li>• PWF/FBT certified lumber</li>
                      <li>• Preservative treated</li>
                      <li>• 75 kPa soil minimum</li>
                      <li>• Granular drainage layer</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                  <div>
                    <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Design Assumptions:</h4>
                    <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                      <li>• Floor spans ≤8m</li>
                      <li>• Live load 1.9 kPa</li>
                      <li>• Stud length ≤3.6m</li>
                      <li>• Earth pressure 4.7 kPa/m</li>
                      <li>• Snow load ≤4 kPa</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <!-- Flat ICF -->
              <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">5. Flat ICF Foundation Walls</h3>
                <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
                  <div>
                    <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Description:</h4>
                    <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                      <li>• Concrete cast in polystyrene</li>
                      <li>• Forms remain in place</li>
                      <li>• Uniform wall thickness</li>
                      <li>• Integrated insulation</li>
                      <li>• Single dwelling units only</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                  <div>
                    <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Limitations:</h4>
                    <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                      <li>• Maximum 2 storeys</li>
                      <li>• 3m floor-to-floor max</li>
                      <li>• 75 kPa soil minimum</li>
                      <li>• No surcharge loads</li>
                      <li>• Stable soil required</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Moisture Control -->
          <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Moisture and Water Control</h2>
            
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-8 border-2 border-gray-300">
              <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Foundation Moisture Protection Requirements</h3>
              
              <div class="space-y-6">
                <div>
                  <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Dampproofing (Section 9.13):</h4>
                  <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                    <li>• Required for all below-grade walls</li>
                    <li>• Extends from footing to finished grade</li>
                    <li>• Bituminous coating or membrane</li>
                    <li>• Protection board recommended</li>
                    <li>• Drainage layer required</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>

                <div>
                  <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Waterproofing (When Required):</h4>
                  <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                    <li>• High water table conditions</li>
                    <li>• Hydrostatic pressure present</li>
                    <li>• Poor drainage conditions</li>
                    <li>• Membrane systems required</li>
                    <li>• Part 4 design typically needed</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="bg-red-50 rounded-lg p-4 border border-red-400">
                  <p class="text-gray-700">
                    <strong>Critical:</strong> Part 9 assumes well-drained conditions with earth pressure of 
                    480 kg/m³. If water table rises creating hydrostatic pressure (1000 kg/m³), the foundation 
                    walls are over-stressed and will fail. Proper drainage is not optional.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Thermal Requirements -->
          <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Thermal Insulation Requirements</h2>
            
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-8 border border-gray-200">
              <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Foundation Insulation Objectives</h3>
              
              <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
                <div>
                  <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Code Minimums Address:</h4>
                  <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                    <li>• Prevention of surface condensation</li>
                    <li>• Occupant comfort conditions</li>
                    <li>• Minimum thermal resistance</li>
                    <li>• Thermal bridge prevention</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Energy Code Adds:</h4>
                  <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                    <li>• Higher R-values required</li>
                    <li>• Full-height insulation</li>
                    <li>• Slab edge insulation</li>
                    <li>• Continuous air barriers</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
                <p class="text-gray-700">
                  <strong>Toronto Practice:</strong> While OBC addresses condensation, most builders install 
                  RSI 2.98 (R-17) minimum for energy efficiency. Full-height interior insulation with vapor 
                  barrier is standard for finished basements.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Soil Gas Protection -->
          <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Soil Gas Protection Requirements</h2>
            
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-8 border-2 border-gray-300">
              <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Foundation Soil Gas Control (Section 9.13.4)</h3>
              
              <div class="space-y-6">
                <div>
                  <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Required Elements:</h4>
                  <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                    <li>• Drainage layer abutting foundation for venting</li>
                    <li>• Continuous air barrier system (Section 9.25.3)</li>
                    <li>• Sealed to basement floor air barrier</li>
                    <li>• All penetrations sealed</li>
                    <li>• Sub-slab depressurization roughed-in</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="bg-yellow-50 rounded-lg p-4 border border-yellow-400">
                  <p class="text-gray-700">
                    <strong>Radon Note:</strong> Toronto has moderate radon potential. Install passive system 
                    (sealed slab, granular layer, capped pipe) during construction. Converting to active system 
                    later costs 5× more than roughing-in now.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Common Problems -->
          <div class="bg-red-50 rounded-lg p-8 mb-12 border-2 border-red-200">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6 flex items-center gap-2">
              <AlertTriangle class="w-6 h-6 text-red-600" />
              Critical Foundation Failures to Avoid
            </h2>
            
            <div class="space-y-4">
              <div>
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Undersized Footings on Poor Soil</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-2">
                  <strong>Problem:</strong> Using Table 9.15.3.4 sizes on soil with &lt;75 kPa capacity
                </p>
                <p class="text-gray-700">
                  <strong>Solution:</strong> Always verify soil bearing capacity. For 50 kPa soil, increase 
                  footing size by 50%. For 40 kPa, double the size or use engineered design.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div>
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Hydrostatic Pressure on Standard Walls</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-2">
                  <strong>Problem:</strong> Water table rise creates pressure double the design capacity
                </p>
                <p class="text-gray-700">
                  <strong>Solution:</strong> Install proper drainage. If high water table possible, use Part 4 
                  design with reinforced walls and waterproofing.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div>
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Frost Action on Piers</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-2">
                  <strong>Problem:</strong> Adfreezing lifts piers even when below frost line
                </p>
                <p class="text-gray-700">
                  <strong>Solution:</strong> Anchor piers to footings, reinforce for tension, backfill with 
                  granular material, or wrap with polyethylene slip plane.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div>
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Fill Settlement</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-2">
                  <strong>Problem:</strong> Building on uncontrolled fill causes differential settlement
                </p>
                <p class="text-gray-700">
                  <strong>Solution:</strong> Never use Part 9 on fill. Require geotechnical investigation and 
                  Part 4 engineered design. Consider deep foundations.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div>
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Inadequate Curing</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-2">
                  <strong>Problem:</strong> Concrete frozen or dried during curing, doesn't reach strength
                </p>
                <p class="text-gray-700">
                  <strong>Solution:</strong> Protect from freezing 72 hours minimum. Keep moist 7 days. 
                  Leave forms in place until set. Never pour on frozen ground.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Footing Size Requirements -->
          <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">OBC Table 9.15.3.4 Footing Sizes</h2>
            
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg overflow-hidden border border-gray-200">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 p-4 bg-gray-50">Minimum Footing Sizes for 75 kPa Soil</h3>
              <table class="w-full">
                <thead class="bg-gray-100">
                  <tr>
                    <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900">Supported Load</th>
                    <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900">Strip Footing Width</th>
                    <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900">Column Footing</th>
                    <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900">Thickness</th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-200">
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Exterior wall, 1 storey</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">250mm (10")</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">N/A</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">100mm (4")</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Exterior wall, 2 storey</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">350mm (14")</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">N/A</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">150mm (6")</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Interior wall, 1 storey</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">200mm (8")</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">N/A</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">100mm (4")</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Interior wall, 2 storey</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">300mm (12")</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">N/A</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">150mm (6")</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Column, 1 storey</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">N/A</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">600×600mm</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">200mm (8")</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Column, 2 storey</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">N/A</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">750×750mm</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">200mm (8")</td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>
            
            <div class="bg-yellow-50 rounded-lg p-4 mt-4 border border-yellow-400">
              <p class="text-gray-700">
                <strong>Adjustment for Poor Soil:</strong> For 50 kPa soil, multiply dimensions by 1.5. 
                For 40 kPa soil, multiply by 1.9. Always round up to nearest 50mm increment.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Construction Sequence -->
          <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Foundation Construction Sequence</h2>
            
            <div class="space-y-4">
              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-6 border-2 border-gray-300">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Phase 1: Site Preparation</h3>
                <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                  <li>✓ Survey and stake building corners</li>
                  <li>✓ Strip topsoil and organic material</li>
                  <li>✓ Excavate to required depth (below frost)</li>
                  <li>✓ Verify soil bearing capacity</li>
                  <li>✓ Install temporary drainage if needed</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-6 border-2 border-gray-300">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Phase 2: Footing Installation</h3>
                <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                  <li>✓ Compact subgrade to 95% SPD</li>
                  <li>✓ Place and compact granular base</li>
                  <li>✓ Set footing forms to correct elevation</li>
                  <li>✓ Install reinforcement if required</li>
                  <li>✓ Pour concrete footings (15-25 MPa)</li>
                  <li>✓ Form keyway for wall connection</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-6 border-2 border-gray-300">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Phase 3: Foundation Walls</h3>
                <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                  <li>✓ Set wall forms or lay first course</li>
                  <li>✓ Install vertical reinforcement</li>
                  <li>✓ Place concrete or build masonry</li>
                  <li>✓ Install anchor bolts for sill plate</li>
                  <li>✓ Cure concrete minimum 7 days</li>
                  <li>✓ Strip forms when adequate strength</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-6 border-2 border-gray-300">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Phase 4: Waterproofing & Drainage</h3>
                <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                  <li>✓ Apply dampproofing/waterproofing</li>
                  <li>✓ Install protection board</li>
                  <li>✓ Place weeping tile at footing level</li>
                  <li>✓ Install granular drainage layer</li>
                  <li>✓ Connect to storm sewer or sump</li>
                  <li>✓ Test drainage system</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-6 border-2 border-gray-300">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Phase 5: Backfill & Finish</h3>
                <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                  <li>✓ Backfill in 300mm lifts</li>
                  <li>✓ Compact each lift to 95% SPD</li>
                  <li>✓ Slope grade away from building (2%)</li>
                  <li>✓ Install window wells if required</li>
                  <li>✓ Place and compact final grade</li>
                  <li>✓ Install surface drainage features</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Design Process -->
          <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Foundation Design Process</h2>
            
            <div class="space-y-4">
              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-6 border border-gray-200">
                <div class="flex gap-4">
                  <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-red-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 font-bold">1</div>
                  <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Verify Site Conditions</h3>
                    <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                      <li>• Soil bearing capacity (geotechnical report)</li>
                      <li>• Water table level and drainage</li>
                      <li>• Frost depth (1.2m in Toronto)</li>
                      <li>• Check for fill, organic soil, contamination</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-6 border border-gray-200">
                <div class="flex gap-4">
                  <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-red-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 font-bold">2</div>
                  <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Determine Design Method</h3>
                    <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                      <li>• If all conditions met: Use Part 9 prescriptive</li>
                      <li>• If soil 40-75 kPa: Use Section 9.4 or Part 4</li>
                      <li>• If any limits exceeded: Require Part 4 engineering</li>
                      <li>• Consider building loads and configuration</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-6 border border-gray-200">
                <div class="flex gap-4">
                  <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-red-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 font-bold">3</div>
                  <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Size Footings</h3>
                    <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                      <li>• Use Table 9.15.3.4 for 75 kPa soil</li>
                      <li>• Adjust for actual bearing capacity</li>
                      <li>• Consider concentrated loads</li>
                      <li>• Minimum depths for frost protection</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-6 border border-gray-200">
                <div class="flex gap-4">
                  <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-red-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 font-bold">4</div>
                  <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Design Walls</h3>
                    <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                      <li>• Select material (concrete, block, ICF, wood)</li>
                      <li>• Size for lateral earth pressure</li>
                      <li>• Check backfill height limits</li>
                      <li>• Design for openings and concentrated loads</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-6 border border-gray-200">
                <div class="flex gap-4">
                  <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-red-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 font-bold">5</div>
                  <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Address Moisture</h3>
                    <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                      <li>• Design drainage system</li>
                      <li>• Specify dampproofing/waterproofing</li>
                      <li>• Plan surface grading</li>
                      <li>• Include granular drainage layers</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-6 border border-gray-200">
                <div class="flex gap-4">
                  <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-red-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 font-bold">6</div>
                  <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Include Protection Systems</h3>
                    <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                      <li>• Thermal insulation strategy</li>
                      <li>• Air barrier continuity</li>
                      <li>• Soil gas control measures</li>
                      <li>• Termite protection where required</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Toronto Specific -->
          <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Toronto-Specific Foundation Challenges</h2>
            
            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
              <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-6">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">Leda Clay Issues</h3>
                <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                  <li>• Sensitive to disturbance</li>
                  <li>• Variable bearing capacity</li>
                  <li>• Seasonal volume changes</li>
                  <li>• Requires careful excavation</li>
                  <li>• Often needs larger footings</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-6">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">High Water Tables</h3>
                <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                  <li>• Common near Lake Ontario</li>
                  <li>• Ravine lots problematic</li>
                  <li>• Seasonal variations</li>
                  <li>• Requires permanent drainage</li>
                  <li>• May need waterproofing</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-6">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">Old Fill Areas</h3>
                <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                  <li>• Historic ravine filling</li>
                  <li>• Unknown composition</li>
                  <li>• Variable settlement</li>
                  <li>• Requires deep foundations</li>
                  <li>• Always needs engineering</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-6">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">Frost Depth</h3>
                <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                  <li>• 1.2m (4 ft) minimum depth</li>
                  <li>• Deeper in open areas</li>
                  <li>• Adfreezing on piers</li>
                  <li>• Frost-protected shallow OK</li>
                  <li>• Insulation alternatives available</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Cost Implications -->
          <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Foundation Cost Factors</h2>
            
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg overflow-hidden border border-gray-200">
              <table class="w-full">
                <thead class="bg-gray-100">
                  <tr>
                    <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900">Foundation Type</th>
                    <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900">Base Cost/m²</th>
                    <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900">Poor Soil Add</th>
                    <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900">Water Issues Add</th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-200">
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Poured concrete</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">$850-1,100</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">+30%</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">+25%</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Concrete block</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">$750-950</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">+30%</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">+30%</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">ICF walls</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">$950-1,200</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">+25%</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">+20%</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Wood frame (PWF)</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">$650-850</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">+35%</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">+40%</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Pier foundation</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">$450-600</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">+50%</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">N/A</td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>
            
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mt-4">
              * Includes excavation, footings, walls, dampproofing, and backfill. Add 15% for finished basement prep.
            </p>
          </div>

          <!-- Conclusion -->
          <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Foundation Success = Understanding Limits</h2>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
              Part 9 prescriptive requirements work perfectly - when all conditions are met. The moment you exceed 
              any limit - soil capacity, building height, water table, fill conditions - you need engineering. 
              Too many failures occur when builders try to stretch Part 9 beyond its boundaries.
            </p>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
              In Toronto, with our challenging soils and variable conditions, we recommend geotechnical investigation 
              for every project. The $2,500 investment reveals whether you can use simple prescriptive design or 
              need engineering. It's the difference between a $50,000 foundation and a $500,000 failure.
            </p>
            <p class="text-gray-700">
              At Toronto Concrete, we've built foundations on everything from solid bedrock to sensitive marine clay. 
              We know when to follow the tables and when to call the engineer. Every foundation starts with understanding 
              the ground beneath - because that's what holds everything up.
            </p>
          </div>

          <!-- CTA -->
          <div class="bg-gray-900 text-white rounded-lg p-8 mt-12 text-center">
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Need Foundation Expertise?</h3>
            <p class="text-lg mb-6">
              From soil analysis to engineered solutions - 39 years of foundation experience
